# Creating Change: The Power of Art in The Climate Movement + A Creative Workshop

Hosted by Karan Rathod, Andy Rapista & SF Climate Week

Apr

21

Monday, April 21

5:30 PM - 8:00 PM PDT

[San Francisco\\
\\
San Francisco, California](https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=San%20Francisco&query_place_id=ChIJIQBpAG2ahYAR_6128GcTUEo)

Welcome! To join the event, please register below.

Register

You will be asked to verify token ownership with your wallet.

About Event

​The sciences are no doubt critical in driving action and influencing climate policy, however, many people are inspired to take action once they have connected with the realities of climate change on an emotional level. This connection can be experienced through stories that move beyond mainstream representations, in the form of art – literature, music, visual art, theatre, film and more.

​This session aims to demonstrate and encourage art as an important mechanism to drive social change, focusing on climate conversations. Our panelists will highlight the role the arts have to play in driving social change, discuss their experiences of how art has had an impact on the climate conversation, and share their own creative projects.

​The session will also include an opportunity for you to workshop your own socially-driven creative ideas with the panelists, where you will leave with the foundations of a new (or existing) creative project.

The event will be co-hosted by [Andy Rapista](https://www.instagram.com/andyrapista/), climate activist and founder of [Mad Earth](https://madtravel.org/) and co-hosted and moderated by Karan Rathod, founder of [Alfaaz](http://www.alfaazcollective.com/) – a literature and arts collective that helps writers and artists get their creative work out, improve literary skills; and to leverage the arts for social change.

_By registering for this event, you agree to share your registration information with the organizers of SF Climate Week._

About Event

​Looking for a relaxed way to meet others who care about climate action and sustainability careers? Bring your lunch, grab a spot on the grass, and connect with professionals, job seekers, and innovators who are working to shape the future of the climate workforce. No formal agenda—just great conversations, fresh air, and a chance to expand your network.

​ **Who Will Be There?**

​🌱 People exploring or transitioning into climate careers

🌍 Sustainability professionals and industry experts

💡 Innovators, educators, founders and workforce leaders

🤝 Recruiters, hiring managers, and career coaches

​ **Why Come?**

- ​Meet like-minded individuals in an informal setting

- ​Share ideas, experiences, and resources

- ​Build meaningful connections—without the pressure of a networking event


​📍 **Location:** Dolores Park

🥪 **What to Bring:** Your lunch, a blanket, and anything to stay comfortable outdoors

🌞 **Vibes:** Casual, welcoming, and collaborative

​Let’s spark new ideas and build a stronger climate community while enjoying some time outside!

​ **Hosted by** [Green Lens Consulting](https://greenlensconsulting.com/) and [SF Climate Week](https://www.sfclimateweek.org/)

Welcome! To join the event, please register below.

Register

You will be asked to verify token ownership with your wallet.

About Event

​How do I turn my breakthrough science into a startup? Am I addressing a problem with a large enough market? How do I recruit a team? Am I the right person to do it?

If you're curious about entrepreneurship, join us to hear Alex Teng, Partner at [Fifty Years](https://www.fiftyyears.com/5050), share insights from helping hundreds of scientists translate breakthrough science into deep tech startups.

We'll dive into how to identify civilization-scale problems to tackle, break down ideas into fundable milestones, develop essential entrepreneurship skills (from hiring to fundraising to negotiating IP), and grow into a great founder.

Fifty Years is an early-stage VC firm. At 50Y, we’ve built deep tech companies ourselves and published the Spinout Playbook, a full guide to spin out of academia. We've backed over 100 deep tech startups and helped them raise over $4.6B.

We've distilled everything we know about deep tech entrepreneurship into 5050, a free program to help great scientists and engineers become great founders.

Whether you're validating an idea or unsure whether entrepreneurship is right for you, see you at Stanford.

Hosted by Stanford SB & Stanford Biotech Group

# Ocean Film Screening - Sequoias of the Sea

Hosted by Ana Blanco & 5 others

Apr

24

Thursday, April 24

6:00 PM - 8:00 PM PDT

Register to See Address

San Francisco, California

Suggested Donation

$25.00

Pay what you want

Welcome! To join the event, please get your ticket below.

Get Ticket

You will be asked to verify token ownership with your wallet.

About Event

​Special Screening of the IOFF Official Selection and Award Winning film Sequoias of the Sea, followed by Q&A with the film directors.

​More than 95% of the kelp forests have disappeared along the Northern California Coast. SEQUOIAS OF THE SEA tells the story of the environmental, cultural and economic destruction impacting a coastal town that has lost its coastal kelp forest. It’s a deep dive into the lives of fishermen, tribes, scientists, and a community working to restore a habitat devastated by a warming climate.

​Be part of the movement to save our underwater forests. Connect with passionate conservationists, engage in meaningful discussions, and learn how we can work together to restore our coastal habitats.

​Reserve your spot today!

​ **Schedule:**

​6:00 PM Arrival, reception and networking

6:15 PM Welcome remarks

6:30 PM **_Sequoias of the Sea_** Documentary Film (54 min)

7:30 PM Panel Discussion with Film Directors Ana Blanco, Natasha Benjamin, and Maria Brown, Superintendent of Greater Farallones NMS/Cordell Bank NMS, Moderated by Jason Britton of NewDay.

8:00 PM Event ends

​“ _By registering for this event, you agree to share your registration information with the organizers of SF Climate Week.”_

# 🧠 The Thought Experiment Lab \[public\]

Hosted by Mendel Liu & The SF Commons

Apr

16

Wednesday, April 16

6:30 PM - 8:00 PM PDT

[550 Laguna St\\
\\
San Francisco, California](https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=550%20Laguna%20St&query_place_id=ChIJQ9xlT6KAhYAReQIfVQZP4ds)

Welcome! To join the event, please register below.

Register

You will be asked to verify token ownership with your wallet.

About Event

​Note: while there are many guests listed in the RSVP, most of these are carried over from previous events in this series. We don't expect much more than 30 to attend.

"Imagination without reason is mere fancy, but reason without imagination is sterile. That is partly why scientists and philosophers alike have always used imaginary scenarios to help sharpen their ideas and push them to their limits." - _The Pig that Wants to be Eaten_, by Julian Baggini

For this meeting (Apr 16), we'll be discussing ethical distinctions brought to light by the trolley problem:

- ​Please read this primer on how to engage with thought experiments: [https://docs.google.com/document/d/1obO4Nb0J5RGNcC-lsy\_lvJdPNcmhq0CXgp2WDytXBpo/edit?usp=sharing](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1obO4Nb0J5RGNcC-lsy_lvJdPNcmhq0CXgp2WDytXBpo/edit?usp=sharing)

- ​It is highly recommended but not required to go deeper by reading this article beforehand: [https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/doing-allowing/](https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/doing-allowing/)


​Some examples of things we've discussed at past meetings:

- ​Could a vegetarian eat a pig with a clear conscience, if that pig wanted to be eaten?

- ​Does a person survive using a teleporter that destroys the body and recreates it with perfect fidelity?

- ​Does the existence of evil in the world pose a problem for belief in a benevolent God?


​We'll be meeting in the 550 Room (down the stairs on the North side). Contact me by text if you're having trouble finding the location.

​On the Wednesdays when we're not running this event, we'll often be having similar discussions here: [https://lu.ma/shortstories](https://lu.ma/shortstories)

Welcome! To join the event, please register below.

Register

You will be asked to verify token ownership with your wallet.

About Event

​ **Join us for a celebration of art, culture, and connection to the land and water on April 26, 2025.**

​Science, art, and culture are linked together, and shape the ways we understand ourselves and the world around us. California Native culture bearers and artists have connected to the land and waters through artistic practice and scientific inquiry since time immemorial. In partnership with the Association of Ramaytush Ohlone and American Indian Cultural District, the Exploratorium welcomes you to the third annual California Native Homeland Festival.

​The celebration will be a sharing of Indigenous artistic and cultural practices that come from deep traditions knowing and living with the California landscape. Don’t miss this opportunity to meet renowned Native artists and cultural bearers, and discover your own relationship with the landscape around us.

​ _Curated in partnership with Gregg Castro (Ramaytush Ohlone, T’rowt’raahl Salinan, Rumsen), cultural director for the Association of Ramaytush Ohlone, and Jennifer Bates (Northern Sierra Mewuk), cultural festival curator and basket weaver._

About Event

​Kick off SF Climate Week with a run in San Francisco's biggest and most beautiful park!

​Ammobia is hosting a run/walk for anyone in the climate tech / hard tech space, interested in starting the week outside, in one of the most beautiful urban parks in the country.

​We'll lead two groups Starting from near Lake Alvord in Golden Gate Park:

- ​A 3km walk around the Conservatory of Flowers \[ [Strava](https://www.strava.com/routes/3324206122505736272)\]

- ​A 7km park loop to a redwood grove, social pace, with different pace groups if needed. \[ [Strava](https://www.strava.com/routes/3324204734139442306)\]


​Both groups will end back near where we start for Coffee and pastries at \[Location TBD\] afterwards.

​If coming from downtown, the N-Judah can drop you off at Stanyan and Carl St, only a few blocks from our start point.

​Ammobia is on a mission to revolutionize the ammonia industry. We are a seed-stage startup developing Haber Bosch 2.0 – a next-generation ammonia synthesis process enabling cost-effective, clean ammonia production. Until now, ammonia production has been a highly polluting, steady-state, high inertia process. We are developing new regimes of physics and plant design that require dynamic processes, especially for ammonia production from intermittent renewable energy sources. Clean ammonia will support ammonia’s growing role in our decarbonized world, tackling some of the most difficult to abate sectors including chemicals, fertilizers, and heavy-duty transportation. We are supported by leading climate tech organizations including Starlight Ventures, Collaborative Fund, Third Derivative, Forbes 30u30, and more.

​Banc of Cal supports tech and life sciences startups with free bank accounts for pre-seed & seed companies, a perks platform, and a team of bankers to support founders as they scale. For VC-backed companies, we offer a non-dilutive venture debt product, lending from $1MM up to $60MM for growth, working capital or runway extension.

​ _By registering for this event, you agree to share your registration information with the organizers of SF Climate Week._

## ​Meet 10 AI Startups on the Demo Floor:

​\- [AI-MD](https://ai-md.com/): Phone-powered scan of 3k+ biomarkers

​\- [ComputerX](https://computerx.ai/): computer-use agents for desktop automation

\- [Exo AI](https://exoai.tech/): AI agents for financial risk analysis

\- [Glamir AI](https://www.glamirai.com/): Personalized AI beauty partner

\- [Guiden AI:](https://guidenai.com/) Enterprise AI agent creation platform

\- [Palona AI:](https://palona.ai/) Drive revenue; delightful AI sales agents

\- [Potpie](https://potpie.ai/): Agents for automating SW dev workflows

\- [Remix AI:](https://www.remix.ing/) Virtual teleportation & spatial intelligence

\- [Synexis](https://synexis.io/): Deal flow intel for investors, startups, enterprises

\- [TensorStax:](http://tensorstax.com/) Autonomous AI for data engineering

Startups can [apply to be featured on the demo floor](https://docs.google.com/forms/d/1zw4T57FaqsxOi3hZFqENrFv2J9hqxapKVlkniCIjCWQ/edit). Minimum of 3/10 demo slots reserved for women founders, last few events were at parity.

## ​ **About Llama Lounge:**

​Since May 2023. We feature 10 AI Startups on a demo floor for personal demos and relationship building with AI founders, investors, and corporate AI leaders. About Event

​Harvest is the smartest HVAC on Earth.

​Come take a live tour of a Harvester's home in the Mission to feel the magic of a Smart Thermal Battery. It's integrated heating, hot water, and air conditioning all in the same system. Not as sexy as an EV, but a lot comfier (and more impactful).

​It's heat pumps, but way smarter (and cheaper).

​More tours - including a happy hour - coming soon. Watch this space.

# SF Climate Week 2025 Energy Hackathon - Hosted by ​Bayou Energy, Palmetto, Shovels, Stepchange, Texture and Virta Ventures

Hosted by James Gordey & 3 others

Apr

21

Monday, April 21

11:00 AM - Apr 22, 11:00 AM PDT

[AWS GenAI Loft\\
\\
San Francisco, California](https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=AWS%20GenAI%20Loft&query_place_id=ChIJYU1rSACBhYAR8gX_suu-tiA)

Approval Required

Your registration is subject to approval by the host.

Welcome! To join the event, please register below.

Request to Join

You will be asked to verify token ownership with your wallet.

About Event

​ [​Bayou Energy](https://www.bayou.energy/), [Palmetto](https://palmetto.com/home-electrification/palmettos-new-energy-intelligence-api), [Shovels](https://www.shovels.ai/), [Stepchange](https://www.stepchange.vc/), [Texture](https://www.texturehq.com/) and [Virta Ventures](https://www.virtaventures.co/), are hosting a 1 day in-person hackathon during San Francisco Climate Week 2025.

​This hackathon is for all–whether you’re just exploring the idea of working in climate to energy veterans. Come with an idea or just some energy and we’ll help you get paired up with a team to get building!

​​If you want to skip the hacking and just see what everyone builds [you can sign up for just the demos here (Tuesday, April 22nd 10-11am PT](https://lu.ma/k46kv4m4)).

​We’ll have a mix of judges from fellow investors— [Russell Sprole from Virta Ventures](https://www.linkedin.com/in/russellsprole/), [Charles Oppenheimer from Oppenheimer Project](https://www.linkedin.com/in/charleso/) and [Tim Connors from PivotNorth Capital](https://www.linkedin.com/in/timothyjconnors/) to active product builders and founders — [Juliet Rothenberg (Product Director of Google Climate AI)](https://www.linkedin.com/in/julietrothenberg/) and [Tom Mercer (VP Product at Rewiring America)](https://www.linkedin.com/in/tomercer/).

​We'll provide you with free access to the Bayou, Palmetto, Shovels and Texture products (details below) as well as other developer resources.

# ​​​Who should attend?

- ​​Software engineers or similarly minded technical folk interested in climate change and how they can help

- ​​Idea to early stage founders and innovators looking to rapidly prototype an idea they're exploring

- ​​Students and job seekers looking for an opportunity to build out their portfolio of work

- ​​Anyone who loves hackathons, data and is interested in trying out new developer tools.


# ​Schedule (all times US Pacific)

- ​ **Monday (4/21)**

  - ​​11 - 11:30 AM: Kickoff

  - ​​11:30 - 12:30 PM: Idea formation and brainstorming with mentors

  - ​​3 - 4 PM: Check in with mentors
- ​ **Tuesday (4/22)**

  - ​ **​10 - 11 AM: Demos and judging**

# ​Product Details

## ​Bayou Energy

​ [Bayou Energy](https://bayou.energy/) provides a suite of APIs for companies to effectively deploy clean energy devices across many utilities.

​Our first product is a utility API that gives companies access to any metered utility data instantly and reliably. The API takes minutes to integrate. Consumers authenticate their utility accounts with one-click, and developers get access to utility account, bill data, and interval meter data in 60 seconds or less from >60% of US utility meters.

​Check out [Bayou’s docs](https://docs.bayou.energy/docs/quickstart) or [get started for free with the product](https://staging.bayou.energy/users/sign_up).

## ​Palmetto

​With nothing more than an address, Palmetto’s Energy Intelligence API returns estimated home energy consumption and production, as granular as hourly, broken down by fuel type and disaggregated to end use. The user may optionally fine-tune estimates by providing any of 60+ attributes about the home, or calibrating on known past energy consumption or production. The user may also pass hypothetical home attributes, allowing them to simulate the impact of home upgrades on the energy footprint.

​The API also returns estimated cost and carbon impact of the home.

​More details about the API can be found [here](https://palmetto.com/home-electrification/palmettos-new-energy-intelligence-api), and full API docs can be accessed at [ei.docs.palmetto.com](http://ei.docs.palmetto.com/). Developers can also make use of the [interactive demo](https://ei.palmetto.com/demo), which allows users to run simulations via a simple UI, complete with visualizations of key outputs.

## ​Shovels

​ **Shovels company/product overview.** **What will participants get access to when participating in the hackathon?**

​ [Shovels](http://shovels.ai/) makes building permit data useful. We continuously track, normalize, and categorize hundreds of millions of building permit records across the country. Shovels enables our customers to explore, profile, and derive actionable insights from our database of residential, commercial, and contractor records.

​Shovels’ API gives customers access nationwide building permit and contractor data, which includes over 170M building permits monthly and 3M contractors. Customers also use Shovels to filter permits by category (e.g. solar, electrification, heat pump, etc.) and to find property, homeowner, and contractor firmagraphic information associated with permit data.

​Link to API documentation [here](https://docs.shovels.ai/api-reference/permits/search-permits).

## ​Texture

​Texture is the **developer platform for energy**—a powerful API-first system designed to help you quickly integrate, analyze, and act on energy data. Whether you’re working with **solar panels, batteries, EV chargers, smart thermostats, or utility data**, Texture gives you the tools to build **smarter, more connected energy apps** without the headache of wrangling messy, inconsistent data.

​ **Why Texture?**

- ​ **Plug & Play APIs** – Get **real-time** access to energy telemetry, utility bill data, geolocation info, and more with simple, well-documented APIs.

- ​ **Intuitive Dashboard** – See your data in action with **powerful visualization tools** that make debugging a breeze.

- ​ **Apps & Integrations** – Extend Texture with **third-party services**, (including **Shovels!)** for rapid data ingestion.

- ​ **Great Docs & Fast Setup** – Get started in minutes, not hours. We’ve built Texture to be as **developer-friendly** as possible.


​ **Get Started**

​The Texture platform is designed to be **fast, flexible, and fun** to build with—perfect for Hackathon projects. Whether you’re making a **next-gen smart home app** or a **grid-aware automation tool**, Texture gives you **the data and tools** to bring it to life.

​Anyone can just go to our website [https://www.texturehq.com](https://www.texturehq.com/) and sign up to get started for free

​API docs with platform concepts documented here at [https://docs.texturehq.com/](https://docs.texturehq.com/) ​

# ​Support and logistics

- ​​The kickoff on Monday and the demos and judging on Tuesday will be held in-person.

- ​​Direct access to the Bayou Energy, Palmetto, Shovels, and Texture team for support and idea brainstorming will be available in-person / in video breakout rooms and Slack. Support hours (US Pacific):

  - ​ **Monday (4/21)**

    - ​ **​12:30 PM - 2:30 PM**

    - ​ **​4:30 PM - 6 PM**
  - ​ **Tuesday (4/22)**

    - ​ **​8:30 - 9:45 AM**
- ​​Product access for Bayou, Shovels, Palmetto and Texture will be provided at no cost.

- ​​Mentors will be available for help during scheduled sessions

Welcome! To join the event, please register below.

Request to Join

About Event

​Most Climate Week events talk about change. This event gives us all a chance to build it. Join us to close out SF Climate Week with creativity, community, and hope.

​

We’ll kick off with a series of fast-paced lightning talks from experts, implementers and funders in the climate space, including from Project Drawdown, Vibrant Data Labs and Kiva — highlighting data and real-world insights on how women-led climate initiatives are consistently underfunded. These quick, compelling shares will set the stage for collective action.

​

From there, the room becomes a workshop. You’ll join a small table group together with the panellists and designers from IDEO [.](https://ideo.org/) orgto use the tools of design futuring to create an object of the future: a tangible artifact that represents the regenerative, gender-just world we’re working toward.

Expect conversation, collaboration, and a creative close to SF Climate Week where you’ll have the opportunity to synthesize everything you’ve learned and questioned during the week. Refreshments and light appetizers by women-owned businesses will be served!

​Last year was such a hit, we're doing it again: break up SF Climate Week with some well deserved wellness. Join the Streamline and A Runners Mind on a social run.

​All paces and abilities are welcome; the only requirement is to bring good energy and an openness to meeting other inspiring folks in the climate space.

Join Waitlist

About Event

​Join [Offstream](https://www.useoffstream.com/) and [M1C](https://m1c.vc/) for an energizing morning networking walk designed for funders and developers in the carbon removal and biomass space. No panels, no pitches - just a chance to meet the right people, spark new ideas, and build valuable connections in a setting that inspires action.

​We’ll take a scenic ~2 mile walk through [Presidio’s Ecology Trail](https://www.alltrails.com/trail/us/california/presidio-ecology-trail), winding through towering redwoods and open grasslands before reaching Inspiration Point Overlook, where we’ll take in panoramic views of the Bay, Alcatraz, and the Golden Gate. Whether you’re an investor looking to meet pioneering project developers or a developer seeking the right partners to scale your work, this is a relaxed, engaging way to build meaningful connections.

When: Tuesday, April 22nd, 9 - 10 AM PST

​Where: Ecology Trail, Presidio, SF

​Who: Carbon removal & biomass funders, developers, and innovators

​RSVP now to take your Climate Week networking beyond the conference room. If you know of a carbon market buyer, offtaker, or developer who should come, invite them too!

Hosted by Ray Beldner & Lilah Beldner

Apr

18

Friday, April 18

2:00 PM - Apr 20, 7:00 PM PDT

[Hotel Del Sol\\
\\
San Francisco, California](https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Hotel%20Del%20Sol&query_place_id=ChIJl2saQtqAhYARP9RISRuhH1U)

Welcome! Please choose your desired ticket type:

Get Ticket

You will be asked to verify token ownership with your wallet.

About Event

​The fair returns **April 18-20, 2025**, to the fun and funky Hotel del Sol, the iconic 1950s motor lodge in the beautiful Marina District adjacent to the Bay, the Palace of Fine Arts, and the Golden Gate Bridge.

​Startup will run concurrently with the prestigious San Francisco Art Fair at Fort Mason, which is within walking distance of the del Sol. By aligning with SF Fair, a cornerstone of the Bay Area art scene since 2011, we're participating in what promises to be an extraordinary weekend of art discovery in San Francisco where tens of thousands of visitors will be coming to discover and buy art.

​Created for artists, by artists, **Startup Art Fair** is a unique platform where independent talents take control of their careers and connect directly with collectors, curators, and art professionals in an intimate boutique hotel setting.

​ **Startup** is a destination event, attracting artists, art industry leaders, and art collectors from across the U.S. and as far away as Mexico, China, Europe, and South America. The fair’s unwavering mission to support creative and professional success for independent artists makes us a beacon for starting and seasoned collectors who seek out unique experiences and innovative brands.

About Event

​You are invited to a Death Café experience where people, often strangers, gather to discuss death.

​The objective is “to increase awareness of death with a view to helping people make the most of their (finite) lives." The experience will be a group discussion of death with no specific agenda. Guidance, suggestions, and conversation starters are offered.

It is a discussion group with community peers rather than a professionally facilitated grief support or counseling session.

Death Café is place for people to talk about death and dying in a supportive, unstructured way.

\*The Death Cafe model was developed by [Jon Underwood](https://deathcafe.com/profile/2/) and [Sue Barsky Reid](http://suebarskyreid.com/), based on the ideas of [Bernard Crettaz](http://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernard_Crettaz).

Welcome! Please choose your desired ticket type:

Get Ticket

About Event

​The fair returns **April 18-20, 2025**, to the fun and funky Hotel del Sol, the iconic 1950s motor lodge in the beautiful Marina District adjacent to the Bay, the Palace of Fine Arts, and the Golden Gate Bridge.

​Startup will run concurrently with the prestigious San Francisco Art Fair at Fort Mason, which is within walking distance of the del Sol. By aligning with SF Fair, a cornerstone of the Bay Area art scene since 2011, we're participating in what promises to be an extraordinary weekend of art discovery in San Francisco where tens of thousands of visitors will be coming to discover and buy art.

​Created for artists, by artists, **Startup Art Fair** is a unique platform where independent talents take control of their careers and connect directly with collectors, curators, and art professionals in an intimate boutique hotel setting.

​ **Startup** is a destination event, attracting artists, art industry leaders, and art collectors from across the U.S. and as far away as Mexico, China, Europe, and South America. The fair’s unwavering mission to support creative and professional success for independent artists makes us a beacon for starting and seasoned collectors who seek out unique experiences and innovative brands.

About Event

​Note: while there are many guests listed in the RSVP, most of these are carried over from previous events in this series. We don't expect much more than 30 to attend.

"Imagination without reason is mere fancy, but reason without imagination is sterile. That is partly why scientists and philosophers alike have always used imaginary scenarios to help sharpen their ideas and push them to their limits." - _The Pig that Wants to be Eaten_, by Julian Baggini

For this meeting (Apr 16), we'll be discussing ethical distinctions brought to light by the trolley problem:

- ​Please read this primer on how to engage with thought experiments: [https://docs.google.com/document/d/1obO4Nb0J5RGNcC-lsy\_lvJdPNcmhq0CXgp2WDytXBpo/edit?usp=sharing](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1obO4Nb0J5RGNcC-lsy_lvJdPNcmhq0CXgp2WDytXBpo/edit?usp=sharing)

- ​It is highly recommended but not required to go deeper by reading this article beforehand: [https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/doing-allowing/](https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/doing-allowing/)


​Some examples of things we've discussed at past meetings:

- ​Could a vegetarian eat a pig with a clear conscience, if that pig wanted to be eaten?

- ​Does a person survive using a teleporter that destroys the body and recreates it with perfect fidelity?

- ​Does the existence of evil in the world pose a problem for belief in a benevolent God?


​We'll be meeting in the 550 Room (down the stairs on the North side). Contact me by text if you're having trouble finding the location.

​On the Wednesdays when we're not running this event, we'll often be having similar discussions here: [https://lu.ma/shortstories](https://lu.ma/shortstories)

Welcome! To join the event, please register below.

Register

You will be asked to verify token ownership with your wallet.

About Event

​ **Join us for a celebration of art, culture, and connection to the land and water on April 26, 2025.**

​Science, art, and culture are linked together, and shape the ways we understand ourselves and the world around us. California Native culture bearers and artists have connected to the land and waters through artistic practice and scientific inquiry since time immemorial. In partnership with the Association of Ramaytush Ohlone and American Indian Cultural District, the Exploratorium welcomes you to the third annual California Native Homeland Festival.

​The celebration will be a sharing of Indigenous artistic and cultural practices that come from deep traditions knowing and living with the California landscape. Don’t miss this opportunity to meet renowned Native artists and cultural bearers, and discover your own relationship with the landscape around us.

​ _Curated in partnership with Gregg Castro (Ramaytush Ohlone, T’rowt’raahl Salinan, Rumsen), cultural director for the Association of Ramaytush Ohlone, and Jennifer Bates (Northern Sierra Mewuk), cultural festival curator and basket weaver._

Apr

9

[Shriram Center for Bioengineering and Chemical Engineering\\
\\
Stanford, California](https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Shriram%20Center%20for%20Bioengineering%20and%20Chemical%20Engineering&query_place_id=ChIJg6i1xtSkj4ARq69LwG9d7jc)

Welcome! To join the event, please register below.

Register

You will be asked to verify token ownership with your wallet.

About Event

​How do I turn my breakthrough science into a startup? Am I addressing a problem with a large enough market? How do I recruit a team? Am I the right person to do it?

If you're curious about entrepreneurship, join us to hear Alex Teng, Partner at [Fifty Years](https://www.fiftyyears.com/5050), share insights from helping hundreds of scientists translate breakthrough science into deep tech startups.

We'll dive into how to identify civilization-scale problems to tackle, break down ideas into fundable milestones, develop essential entrepreneurship skills (from hiring to fundraising to negotiating IP), and grow into a great founder.

Fifty Years is an early-stage VC firm. At 50Y, we’ve built deep tech companies ourselves and published the Spinout Playbook, a full guide to spin out of academia. We've backed over 100 deep tech startups and helped them raise over $4.6B.

We've distilled everything we know about deep tech entrepreneurship into 5050, a free program to help great scientists and engineers become great founders.

Whether you're validating an idea or unsure whether entrepreneurship is right for you, see you at Stanford.

Hosted by Stanford SB & Stanford Biotech Group

About Event

​Join Forliance for an engaging **Carbon Markets Happy Hour: Meet the Nature-Based Innovators** on **April 22 at Manny's**. Connect with industry leaders, sustainability professionals, and climate investors over drinks as we explore the latest in **nature-based carbon solutions**. Discover how high-quality reforestation projects drive impact, support biodiversity, and shape the future of carbon markets. Don't miss this chance to network and gain insights into the evolving landscape of climate finance!

​

​ _By registering for this event, you agree to share your registration information with the organizers of SF Climate Week._

About Event

​ **✨ Barre, Brunch & Baubles ✨**

​Get ready for a morning of movement, connection, and a little sparkle! 💫 **Barre, Brunch & Baubles** is the perfect way to treat yourself and your besties to a wellness experience that blends fitness, fun, and creativity.

​We’ll start with a **dynamic barre class** designed to tone and sculpt while leaving you feeling strong and energized. After class, refuel with a **delicious bagel bar**, complete with a variety of toppings to customize your perfect post-workout bite. Then, add a little extra shine to your day with a **permanent jewelry experience or bracelet making**, where you can create a custom keepsake to take home.

​✨ **What’s included:**

💪 A **barre class** to strengthen and tone

🥯 A **bagel bar** with fresh, delicious options

💎 Your choice of **permanent jewelry or bracelet making**

​\*Permanent jewelry is available at an additional cost and is not included in your ticket. If you prefer, you can join us for bracelet making instead!

​Come for the workout, stay for the brunch, and leave with a little sparkle! ✨

​Spots are limited, RSVP today!

Apr

12

Register to See Address

San Francisco, California

Request to Join

About Event

## ​ _/ YOU'VE BEEN ACCEPTED ? ConGrAtS ! Now, PLEASE BUILD YOUR TEAMS ON_ _[DISCORD](https://discord.gg/Y3TFTmE89g)_ _PRIOR TO DAY-0 /_/    **👾** **[Re-Weird the Web](https://hackathon-website-blush.vercel.app/)** **\- SF Hackathon 👾**

​​ **Go WeIRd oR go hoMe**

​ [Ariana.dev](https://ariana.dev/), [Entrepreneurs First](https://www.joinef.com/) & [PostHog](https://posthog.com/) are joining forces to bring the ultimate hackathon event of SF.

​People used to have fun on the internet. There were fewer trolls, bots, ads and content farms. Web creators made straight-up magical wonders. These days, everything looks like Tailwind and smells like AI, and nobody’s making real art. **THAT’S ALL ABOUT TO CHANGE.**

​Come together for two days with creative coders who are bringing skill, imagination and weirdness back to product development: the only hackathon where you can make anything you want, as long as you make it **WeIRd**.

​

* * *

## ​​​🏆 **The Challenge - 3 TRACKS**

1. ​ **Games:** Playable, interactive experiences. Bring the most absurd game to life, where you and your friends can finally live your wildest dreams— step into Jeremy shoes & launch blue oranges to the moon, soar over seas of bugs as a hero from Ancient Mythology, or simply achieve the impossible: get your commit reviewed in under three days.

2. ​ **Satire & Humor:** Memes, parodies, and spoofs that cut deep. Invent a Vs-code extension that randomly spawns fresh bugs following a NP-complete algorithm.

Launch the ultimate recursive grift : marketplace of markeplatce of marketplace of ... (while (true) { marketplace = `${marketplace} of ${marketplace}`; } ) . Because you can. & Because capitalism.

Design the utmost dystopian app: AI-generated cats in a blender. ( _Yes, it’s tragic. But hey, now you can afford those overpriced eggs during the next inevitable shortage_.)

In short : Go wild. Make us cry. Make us laugh.

3. ​ **Actually That’s Quite Useful: Apps that make you say “actually that’s quite useful.”**


​

* * *

## ​​​🗓️ **Event Details**

- ​​​ **Date:** Saturday, April 12th (9AM to 21PM)

- ​​ **Location** : in the exceptional offices of [Entrepreneurs First](https://www.joinef.com/) in the heart of SF -> in person event

- ​​​ **Participants:** 100 spots

- ​​​ **Prizes:** Plushes, Hoodies, FuN & more to come


* * *

## ​​​🍱 The **set-up (Teams & Food)**

​​​We’ll be providing **delicious food and drinks** to keep you fueled throughout the event.

​Teams should consist of **3 to 5 participants**, with each person required to register and be individually accepted. No teams? No worries, we will help making sure you find teammates prior to the event.

​Please note, **this is an in-person event,** and online participation will not be available.

* * *

## ​​​🎁 **What's in it for you** ​

​ _FUN - ART - CREATIVITY - Curiouser & Curiouser? Welcome to Wonderland._

​​​Lots of updates on the jury, mentors, ressources, and prizes coming soon!

* * *

## ​​​ **🌠** **Guidelines**

​Participants should …

- ​Develop using common web development languages and frameworks: ie, JavaScript/TypeScript for frontend or backend (Node.js), Python, Ruby, PHP, etc.

- ​Build for the web, and make it **Good Weird.**


​ **What is Good Weird?**

- ​ **Bad Weird**: Your product is soulless, mean and corporate. It makes people’s eyes glaze over. It has bugs. \|

- ​ **Good Weird**: Your product sparks joy.  It makes your ICP smile. It has one bug, Jeremy. He’s your mascot.


​ **Can I use AI when building at this hackathon?**

​Yes, you can use AI, but with taste. Don’t automate the humanity out of your project. And yes, that’s highly subjective.

About Event

​Join [Offstream](https://www.useoffstream.com/) and [M1C](https://m1c.vc/) for an energizing morning networking walk designed for funders and developers in the carbon removal and biomass space. No panels, no pitches - just a chance to meet the right people, spark new ideas, and build valuable connections in a setting that inspires action.

​We’ll take a scenic ~2 mile walk through [Presidio’s Ecology Trail](https://www.alltrails.com/trail/us/california/presidio-ecology-trail), winding through towering redwoods and open grasslands before reaching Inspiration Point Overlook, where we’ll take in panoramic views of the Bay, Alcatraz, and the Golden Gate. Whether you’re an investor looking to meet pioneering project developers or a developer seeking the right partners to scale your work, this is a relaxed, engaging way to build meaningful connections.

When: Tuesday, April 22nd, 9 - 10 AM PST

​Where: Ecology Trail, Presidio, SF

​Who: Carbon removal & biomass funders, developers, and innovators

​RSVP now to take your Climate Week networking beyond the conference room. If you know of a carbon market buyer, offtaker, or developer who should come, invite them too!

Welcome! To join the event, please get your ticket below.

Request to Join

You will be asked to verify token ownership with your wallet.

About Event

​ _[SuperHuman Society](http://sprhmn.org/)_ _&_ _[Imbue](http://imbue.com/)_ _Presents “Visions of the Future Hackathon”_

​ **Where is humanity headed as AI, robotics, and other breakthrough tech reshape our world?**

​If you've ever imagined how our future might look like, this event is for you.

​Join us for a non-technical hackathon where curious minds come together to envision tomorrow's utopia… or dystopia, through short stories ( [vignettes](https://morereasonable.com/)) paired with AI-generated visual art.

​Teams will collaborate, build on each other's ideas, and create shared visions of possible futures. The final outputs will be compiled into a **physical book** and locked into a **digital time capsule**, capturing our collective hopes, dreams, and fears in this exact point in history.

​ **Who is this event for?**

- ​Technologists

- ​Social Scientists, Philosophers, Historians

- ​Futurists

- ​Artists

- ​Anyone and everyone who cares about our collective future.


​ **What You'll Do**

- ​ **Join a Team:** Get matched with other participants at the start of the event to form diverse teams that blend technical insight, artistic vision, and storytelling.

- ​ **Collaborate & Storyboard:** Work together to explore and expand each other's ideas into rich future scenarios. Brainstorm possible scenarios—maybe post-labor world or a society run by nano-robots—and shape them into short, compelling storyboards through group ideation and refinement.

- ​ **Make it Visual:** Bring these imaginations to life through AI-generated art.

- ​ **Create a Lasting Record:** See your team's work published in a physical book and preserved online, solidifying your collective voice in the conversation about humanity's next chapter.

- ​ **Get Inspired & Connect:** Enjoy talks from guest speakers, connect with fellow humans.


​ **Why is there a $20 ticket price?**

​We’re asking for a small fee to ensure commitment—free events often suffer from unpredictable turnout. Your ticket helps create a high-quality experience for all attendees.

​ **What’s included?**

Coffee & snacks in the morning

Lunch to fuel your creativity

Happy hour with light bites to celebrate and connect

​ **Where does the money go?**

Proceeds will help us place printed copies of the final book in public spaces, ensuring that the visions we create together are shared widely and spark meaningful conversations.

​Whether you're excited about tomorrow's possibilities or worried about the risks, you have a place here.

​ **Come add your voice—and vision—to our shared future.**

​Organizers:

​ _The_ **_[SuperHuman Society](http://sprhmn.org/)_** _exists for those who refuse to accept a dehumanized future. We bring together thinkers, founders, artists, and technologists committed to designing a world where technology amplifies human dignity instead of diminishing it._

​ **_[Imbue](https://imbue.com/)_** seeks to radically expand what computing can do for people and to distribute its creative power to all.

About Event

​Replate is excited to host a dynamic panel discussion during SF Climate Week, exploring the transformative power of AI in tackling global challenges. This engaging conversation will highlight how AI can be harnessed for good, revolutionizing industries traditionally reliant on manual processes. The panel will feature Maen Mahfoud, CEO of Replate; Emin, CEO of Rubbish; Diz Petit, CEO of Liquidonate; and Sarika Bajaj, CEO of Refiberd—leaders at the forefront of AI-driven innovation in sustainability. Together, they will share insights and real-world applications of AI that drive efficiency, sustainability, and meaningful impact. Join us for an inspiring discussion on the future of AI in building a more sustainable world.

About Event

# ​ **Let's hang!**

​​​Join Hustle Fund and the SF founder community to connect with other founders and hear from an entrepreneur with wild stories and expert advice.

# ​Meet Humphrey Yang

![User Uploaded Image](https://images.lumacdn.com/cdn-cgi/image/format=auto,fit=cover,dpr=2,quality=75,width=800,height=800/editor-images/3y/9401577f-8451-491f-83b9-6640b67fdeb5.jpg)

​Humphrey is the world's largest financial advice YouTuber.

​Humphrey is the founder and CEO of [HumphreyTalks](https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCFBpVaKCC0ajGps1vf0AgBg), a brand with over 4 million subscribers across YouTube and social media.

​When I think of a financial advisor, I think of a boomer in a dusty suit sitting behind a desk using words I don't understand.

​That is not Humphrey. Humphrey covers everything from investing and entrepreneurship to tax hacks and personal finance in a way that's digestible... and without a trace of BS.

​His on-camera persona is kind of like a super nice big brother — he knows way more than you, but he's willing to share his knowledge because he genuinely wants you to thrive.

​So what makes Humphrey qualified to give +4 million people financial advice?

​He spent years in finance, working at JPMorgan before launching his own e-commerce ventures. His deep understanding of both Wall Street and online business gave him an edge in explaining complex financial topics in a way that actually makes sense.

​Since launching HumphreyTalks, his influence has exploded. His content reaches hundreds of millions of views annually, and he’s turned his media brand into a powerhouse, partnering with major financial platforms, fintech startups, and global brands.

​Now, Humphrey isn’t just educating — he’s building. Through strategic investments, partnerships, and new media ventures, he’s redefining what it means to be a creator in finance. He’s proving that the next generation of financial education won’t come from institutions — it’ll come from dynamic, trusted voices like his.

​​​Join us on Monday, April 28, for a fireside chat with Humphrey to hear about his journey building a modern media empire, including the largest financial advice YouTube channel in the world.

# ​​The Schedule

​6-6:30pm: Get here, eat pizza, make friends

​​​6:30-7pm: Fireside chat - Humphrey Yang

​​​7-7:30pm: Audience Q&A

​​​7:30-8:30pm: Finish pizza, make more friends

​​​8:30pm: See you next time, SF!

​Last year was such a hit, we're doing it again: break up SF Climate Week with some well deserved wellness. Join the Streamline and A Runners Mind on a social run.

​ _In an effort to reduce waste, please bring your own mug for coffee ☕️_

​ **Route:** **[Strava Link](https://www.strava.com/routes/3215126614834034584)**

​All paces and abilities are welcome; the only requirement is to bring good energy and an openness to meeting other inspiring folks in the climate space.

**7am** \- Meet. We'll mingle, grab coffee, and cover the route. ASICS is bringing demo shoes to try - come early to grab a pair 👟. _Remember, bring your own mug for coffee ☕️_

**7:15** \- Start running!

**8am** \- Coffee and Donuts! We'll reconvene at A Runner's Mind for coffee and donuts.

​Hit off Monday strong and join fellow climate and racquet enthusiasts for a padel & pickleball tournament on Treasure Island!

​Enjoy 2 hours of match play, networking, and light breakfast bites. Beginner to expert – all levels are welcome!

​Treasure Island is an easy 15 min drive (or 5 min ferry ride) from downtown SF. Attendees can carpool back together post-match. Please arrive in athletic clothing and sneakers. There are dressing rooms with showers at the facility for those who leave it all on the court and break a sweat. All equipment will be provided, and there will be space to store backpacks and laptops.

# Future of Web Hackathon

[All Things Web](https://lu.ma/allthingsweb?k=c)

Apr

26

Saturday, April 26

10:30 AM - 8:30 PM PDT

[Sentry\\
\\
San Francisco, California](https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Sentry&query_place_id=ChIJIcPaect_j4ARRBpzuVR08hc)

Welcome! To join the event, please register below.

Register

You will be asked to verify token ownership with your wallet.

About Event

​​Join us for a day of hacking the web! Collaborate, create, and compete for two awards while bringing your ideas to life!

## ​​ **When & Where**

​April 26 (Sat), at the Sentry office in San Francisco! Doors will open at 10:30 am.

## ​​ **Awards and** Prizes

​​At the end of the event, we’ll vote for the most creative and most impactful projects. The winning teams will score some awesome prizes! Stay tuned as we'll announce the prizes soon!

## ​​Theme

​"Future of Web" is the theme for this hackathon. Let's imagine the future of web UI, interactions, and AI. Please feel free to work on whatever else sparks your interest though.

## ​​ **Team Matching**

​It's not required to bring a team, though you can bring friends, team up on the spot, or fly solo if that’s more your style. We’ll kick things off with some fun icebreakers and socializing. Teaming up isn’t mandatory, but it’s an awesome way to make new friends!

## ​​Schedule

- ​​10:30 am - Doors open

- ​​11:00 am - Kick-off presentation

- ​​1 - 7:30 pm - Hacking time

- ​​7:30 pm - Presentations & awards ceremony

- ​​8:30 pm - Closing doors


## ​​ **Sponsors**

​​This hackathon is hosted and made possible by Sentry!

​​Sentry is the debuggability platform built for how modern developers work. Over 4 million developers worldwide trust Sentry’s opinionated approach to debugging—favoring action over dashboards—which gives them the context and code level visibility they need to solve issues fast. Sentry users spend more time building and less time firefighting.

## ​​About All Things Web​​​​

​​We are a group of web enthusiasts who love to bring the community together and chat about all things web! Subscribe to [our Luma calendar](https://lu.ma/allthingsweb) for upcoming events, visit [allthingsweb.dev](http://allthingsweb.dev/) to learn more, and [join our Discord](https://discord.gg/B3Sm4b5mfD) server to stay connected.

About Event

​Climate work is hard. How do we replenish our fighting energy? How do we open our minds to new ideas? How do we lift our spirits? Art helps! It can be beautiful, emotional, joyful, and even funny. It can convey ideas when words fall short.

​Come experience a curated collection of regional artists responding to climate issues.

​The evening will include a discussion with artists, playful opportunities to create, and ample time to connect with others.

​Co-hosted by  Climate Reality Bay Area, focused on promoting climate action and climate justice in the region and The Drawing Room Inc, dedicated to bringing people together by harnessing a vibrant and local community network through art.

# Living Sustainably with Wildfire: Science for Solutions

[Western Fire & Forest Resilience Collaborative Events](https://lu.ma/calendar/cal-UCs3ujQz9p3UJwl)

Apr

24

Thursday, April 24

5:00 PM - 6:00 PM PDT

Register to See Address

San Francisco, California

Approval Required

Your registration is subject to approval by the host.

Welcome! To join the event, please register below.

Request to Join

You will be asked to verify token ownership with your wallet.

Have an access code? You can enter it here.

About Event

​Join us for a panel discussion on how changing wildfire activity is affecting ecosystems, water resources, and communities, and the importance of science for solutions. The panel is hosted by the Western Fire and Forest Resilience Collaborative and the Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation.

​Our panelists Lori Moore-Merrell, Hilary Franz, Lara Kueppers, and Winslow Hansen will discuss lessons learned from the LA fires and similar events, regional trends in fire, and risks to water resources and forest health. Panelists will share their experience with the use of science to inform strategies for managing fire in communities, ecosystems, and where they mix.

​The conversation will be of interest for anyone concerned with fire, water resources, or climate resilience. Learn how science-based solutions can build resilience in a rapidly changing environment.

​ **Panel Members:**

​ **Lori Moore-Merrell,** Former US Fire Administrator in the Biden Administration

​ **Hilary Franz,** Former Washington State Commissioner of Public Lands

​ **Lara Kueppers,** Professor of Climate Change and Ecosystem Dynamics, UC Berkeley

​ **Winslow Hansen,** Director Western Fire and Forest Resilience Collaborative and Assistant Scientist, Cary Institute of Ecosystem Studies

​ [https://www.westernfireforest.org/](https://www.westernfireforest.org/)

​ _By registering for this event, you agree to share your registration information with the organizers of SF Climate Week._

​​ _By participating in the event you consent to be photographed, videoed and recorded. Photos, videos and recordings may be used publicly for promotional purposes_

# Living Sustainably with Wildfire: Science for Solutions

[Western Fire & Forest Resilience Collaborative Events](https://lu.ma/calendar/cal-UCs3ujQz9p3UJwl)

Apr

24

Thursday, April 24

5:00 PM - 6:00 PM PDT

Register to See Address

San Francisco, California

Approval Required

Your registration is subject to approval by the host.

Welcome! To join the event, please register below.

Request to Join

You will be asked to verify token ownership with your wallet.

Have an access code? You can enter it here.

About Event

​Join us for a panel discussion on how changing wildfire activity is affecting ecosystems, water resources, and communities, and the importance of science for solutions. The panel is hosted by the Western Fire and Forest Resilience Collaborative and the Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation.

​Our panelists Lori Moore-Merrell, Hilary Franz, Lara Kueppers, and Winslow Hansen will discuss lessons learned from the LA fires and similar events, regional trends in fire, and risks to water resources and forest health. Panelists will share their experience with the use of science to inform strategies for managing fire in communities, ecosystems, and where they mix.

​The conversation will be of interest for anyone concerned with fire, water resources, or climate resilience. Learn how science-based solutions can build resilience in a rapidly changing environment.

​ **Panel Members:**

​ **Lori Moore-Merrell,** Former US Fire Administrator in the Biden Administration

​ **Hilary Franz,** Former Washington State Commissioner of Public Lands

​ **Lara Kueppers,** Professor of Climate Change and Ecosystem Dynamics, UC Berkeley

​ **Winslow Hansen,** Director Western Fire and Forest Resilience Collaborative and Assistant Scientist, Cary Institute of Ecosystem Studies

​ [https://www.westernfireforest.org/](https://www.westernfireforest.org/)

​ _By registering for this event, you agree to share your registration information with the organizers of SF Climate Week._

​​ _By participating in the event you consent to be photographed, videoed and recorded. Photos, videos and recordings may be used publicly for promotional purposes_

# Death Cafe - Downtown Berkeley Central Library

Hosted by Jason Popko

Apr

26

Saturday, April 26

10:00 AM - 12:00 PM PDT

[Berkeley Public Library\\
\\
Berkeley, California](https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Berkeley%20Public%20Library&query_place_id=ChIJx9e2_px-hYARsVoF7Q_SXrY)

Welcome! Please choose your desired ticket type:

Register

You will be asked to verify token ownership with your wallet.

Suggested price shown. Name your own price at checkout.

About Event

​You are invited to a Death Café experience where people, often strangers, gather to discuss death.

​The objective is “to increase awareness of death with a view to helping people make the most of their (finite) lives." The experience will be a group discussion of death with no specific agenda. Guidance, suggestions, and conversation starters are offered.

It is a discussion group with community peers rather than a professionally facilitated grief support or counseling session.

Death Café is place for people to talk about death and dying in a supportive, unstructured way.

\*The Death Cafe model was developed by [Jon Underwood](https://deathcafe.com/profile/2/) and [Sue Barsky Reid](http://suebarskyreid.com/), based on the ideas of [Bernard Crettaz](http://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernard_Crettaz).

Location

Berkeley Public Library

2090 Kittredge St, Berkeley, CA 94704, USA

The Community Meeting Room at Central is located in the 3rd floor

About Event

​ [​Bayou Energy](https://www.bayou.energy/), [Palmetto](https://palmetto.com/home-electrification/palmettos-new-energy-intelligence-api), [Shovels](https://www.shovels.ai/), [Stepchange](https://www.stepchange.vc/), [Texture](https://www.texturehq.com/) and [Virta Ventures](https://www.virtaventures.co/), are hosting a 1 day in-person hackathon during San Francisco Climate Week 2025.

​This hackathon is for all–whether you’re just exploring the idea of working in climate to energy veterans. Come with an idea or just some energy and we’ll help you get paired up with a team to get building!

​​If you want to skip the hacking and just see what everyone builds [you can sign up for just the demos here (Tuesday, April 22nd 10-11am PT](https://lu.ma/k46kv4m4)).

​We’ll have a mix of judges from fellow investors— [Russell Sprole from Virta Ventures](https://www.linkedin.com/in/russellsprole/), [Charles Oppenheimer from Oppenheimer Project](https://www.linkedin.com/in/charleso/) and [Tim Connors from PivotNorth Capital](https://www.linkedin.com/in/timothyjconnors/) to active product builders and founders — [Juliet Rothenberg (Product Director of Google Climate AI)](https://www.linkedin.com/in/julietrothenberg/) and [Tom Mercer (VP Product at Rewiring America)](https://www.linkedin.com/in/tomercer/).

​We'll provide you with free access to the Bayou, Palmetto, Shovels and Texture products (details below) as well as other developer resources.

# ​​​Who should attend?

- ​​Software engineers or similarly minded technical folk interested in climate change and how they can help

- ​​Idea to early stage founders and innovators looking to rapidly prototype an idea they're exploring

- ​​Students and job seekers looking for an opportunity to build out their portfolio of work

- ​​Anyone who loves hackathons, data and is interested in trying out new developer tools.


# ​Schedule (all times US Pacific)

- ​ **Monday (4/21)**

  - ​​11 - 11:30 AM: Kickoff

  - ​​11:30 - 12:30 PM: Idea formation and brainstorming with mentors

  - ​​3 - 4 PM: Check in with mentors
- ​ **Tuesday (4/22)**

  - ​ **​10 - 11 AM: Demos and judging**

# ​Product Details

## ​Bayou Energy

​ [Bayou Energy](https://bayou.energy/) provides a suite of APIs for companies to effectively deploy clean energy devices across many utilities.

​Our first product is a utility API that gives companies access to any metered utility data instantly and reliably. The API takes minutes to integrate. Consumers authenticate their utility accounts with one-click, and developers get access to utility account, bill data, and interval meter data in 60 seconds or less from >60% of US utility meters.

​Check out [Bayou’s docs](https://docs.bayou.energy/docs/quickstart) or [get started for free with the product](https://staging.bayou.energy/users/sign_up).

## ​Palmetto

​With nothing more than an address, Palmetto’s Energy Intelligence API returns estimated home energy consumption and production, as granular as hourly, broken down by fuel type and disaggregated to end use. The user may optionally fine-tune estimates by providing any of 60+ attributes about the home, or calibrating on known past energy consumption or production. The user may also pass hypothetical home attributes, allowing them to simulate the impact of home upgrades on the energy footprint.

​The API also returns estimated cost and carbon impact of the home.

​More details about the API can be found [here](https://palmetto.com/home-electrification/palmettos-new-energy-intelligence-api), and full API docs can be accessed at [ei.docs.palmetto.com](http://ei.docs.palmetto.com/). Developers can also make use of the [interactive demo](https://ei.palmetto.com/demo), which allows users to run simulations via a simple UI, complete with visualizations of key outputs.

## ​Shovels

​ **Shovels company/product overview.** **What will participants get access to when participating in the hackathon?**

​ [Shovels](http://shovels.ai/) makes building permit data useful. We continuously track, normalize, and categorize hundreds of millions of building permit records across the country. Shovels enables our customers to explore, profile, and derive actionable insights from our database of residential, commercial, and contractor records.

​Shovels’ API gives customers access nationwide building permit and contractor data, which includes over 170M building permits monthly and 3M contractors. Customers also use Shovels to filter permits by category (e.g. solar, electrification, heat pump, etc.) and to find property, homeowner, and contractor firmagraphic information associated with permit data.

​Link to API documentation [here](https://docs.shovels.ai/api-reference/permits/search-permits).

## ​Texture

​Texture is the **developer platform for energy**—a powerful API-first system designed to help you quickly integrate, analyze, and act on energy data. Whether you’re working with **solar panels, batteries, EV chargers, smart thermostats, or utility data**, Texture gives you the tools to build **smarter, more connected energy apps** without the headache of wrangling messy, inconsistent data.

​ **Why Texture?**

- ​ **Plug & Play APIs** – Get **real-time** access to energy telemetry, utility bill data, geolocation info, and more with simple, well-documented APIs.

- ​ **Intuitive Dashboard** – See your data in action with **powerful visualization tools** that make debugging a breeze.

- ​ **Apps & Integrations** – Extend Texture with **third-party services**, (including **Shovels!)** for rapid data ingestion.

- ​ **Great Docs & Fast Setup** – Get started in minutes, not hours. We’ve built Texture to be as **developer-friendly** as possible.


​ **Get Started**

​The Texture platform is designed to be **fast, flexible, and fun** to build with—perfect for Hackathon projects. Whether you’re making a **next-gen smart home app** or a **grid-aware automation tool**, Texture gives you **the data and tools** to bring it to life.

​Anyone can just go to our website [https://www.texturehq.com](https://www.texturehq.com/) and sign up to get started for free

​API docs with platform concepts documented here at [https://docs.texturehq.com/](https://docs.texturehq.com/) ​

# ​Support and logistics

- ​​The kickoff on Monday and the demos and judging on Tuesday will be held in-person.

- ​​Direct access to the Bayou Energy, Palmetto, Shovels, and Texture team for support and idea brainstorming will be available in-person / in video breakout rooms and Slack. Support hours (US Pacific):

  - ​ **Monday (4/21)**

    - ​ **​12:30 PM - 2:30 PM**

    - ​ **​4:30 PM - 6 PM**
  - ​ **Tuesday (4/22)**

    - ​ **​8:30 - 9:45 AM**
- ​​Product access for Bayou, Shovels, Palmetto and Texture will be provided at no cost.

- ​​Mentors will be available for help during scheduled sessions

# ​Join Heatmap at SF Climate Week!

​Solar, wind and lithium-ion battery storage are proven winners in the clean energy economy, but what is the next suite of technologies and tools that will help accelerate the path to achieving global climate goals? Join Heatmap journalists along with industry leaders, investors, and experts to discuss the most promising up and coming climate tech solutions.

## ​ **Agenda**

​ **​5:00pm: Doors Open**

**​5:30pm: Opening Remarks from** **[Nico Lauricella](https://www.linkedin.com/in/nico-lauricella-19020619/)** **, CEO and Editor-in-Chief, Heatmap News**

​ **5:35pm:** **Where Climate Tech Goes Next: A Conversation with Tom Steyer**

​Tom Steyer, Co-Executive Chair of Galvanize Climate Solutions and a leading climate investor, will still down with Heatmap Executive Editor Robinson Meyer to explore the most promising technologies to scale, the policy and financial support needed to accelerate them, and market-driven strategies to drive the next generation of climate tech breakthroughs.

​ _Featuring_ _[Tom Steyer](https://www.tomsteyer.com/)_ _, Co-Executive Chair, Galvanize Climate Solutions, moderated by_ _[Robinson Meyer](https://www.linkedin.com/in/robinsonmeyer/)_ _, Executive Editor, Heatmap News_

​ **6:00pm:** **Lightning Talk**

​ **6:10pm:** **Betting on the Future: Scaling Climate Tech**

​As climate technologies rapidly evolve, where are investors placing their bets – and what does it take to turn those emerging innovations into the next unicorn? This panel will explore the disruptive technologies capturing VCs attention and how investors identify and scale the next generation of climate tech breakthroughs.

​ _Moderated by_ _[Katie Brigham](https://www.linkedin.com/in/katie-brigham-20a71039/)_ _, Staff Writer, Heatmap News_

​ **6:45pm:** **Networking & Happy Hour**

​

About Event

# ​Join Heatmap at SF Climate Week!

​Solar, wind and lithium-ion battery storage are proven winners in the clean energy economy, but what is the next suite of technologies and tools that will help accelerate the path to achieving global climate goals? Join Heatmap journalists along with industry leaders, investors, and experts to discuss the most promising up and coming climate tech solutions.

## ​ **Agenda**

​ **​5:00pm: Doors Open**

**​5:30pm: Opening Remarks from** **[Nico Lauricella](https://www.linkedin.com/in/nico-lauricella-19020619/)** **, CEO and Editor-in-Chief, Heatmap News**

​ **5:35pm:** **Where Climate Tech Goes Next: A Conversation with Tom Steyer**

​Tom Steyer, Co-Executive Chair of Galvanize Climate Solutions and a leading climate investor, will still down with Heatmap Executive Editor Robinson Meyer to explore the most promising technologies to scale, the policy and financial support needed to accelerate them, and market-driven strategies to drive the next generation of climate tech breakthroughs.

​ _Featuring_ _[Tom Steyer](https://www.tomsteyer.com/)_ _, Co-Executive Chair, Galvanize Climate Solutions, moderated by_ _[Robinson Meyer](https://www.linkedin.com/in/robinsonmeyer/)_ _, Executive Editor, Heatmap News_

​ **6:00pm:** **Lightning Talk**

​ **6:10pm:** **Betting on the Future: Scaling Climate Tech**

​As climate technologies rapidly evolve, where are investors placing their bets – and what does it take to turn those emerging innovations into the next unicorn? This panel will explore the disruptive technologies capturing VCs attention and how investors identify and scale the next generation of climate tech breakthroughs.

​ _Moderated by_ _[Katie Brigham](https://www.linkedin.com/in/katie-brigham-20a71039/)_ _, Staff Writer, Heatmap News_

​ **6:45pm:** **Networking & Happy Hour**

​

* * *

​ _By registering, you agree to receive emails from Heatmap, including event-related communications and future updates, and consent to your image or likeness being used in event-related content._

​ _​We are looking for a couple volunteers to help out at the event. If interested, reach out to jill@heatmap.news!_

​ _By registering for this event, you agree to share your registration information with the organizers of SF Climate Week._

About Event

​Special Screening of the IOFF Official Selection and Award Winning film Sequoias of the Sea, followed by Q&A with the film directors.

​More than 95% of the kelp forests have disappeared along the Northern California Coast. SEQUOIAS OF THE SEA tells the story of the environmental, cultural and economic destruction impacting a coastal town that has lost its coastal kelp forest. It’s a deep dive into the lives of fishermen, tribes, scientists, and a community working to restore a habitat devastated by a warming climate.

​Be part of the movement to save our underwater forests. Connect with passionate conservationists, engage in meaningful discussions, and learn how we can work together to restore our coastal habitats.

​Reserve your spot today!

​ **Schedule:**

​6:00 PM Arrival, reception and networking

6:15 PM Welcome remarks

6:30 PM **_Sequoias of the Sea_** Documentary Film (54 min)

7:30 PM Panel Discussion with Film Directors Ana Blanco, Natasha Benjamin, and Maria Brown, Superintendent of Greater Farallones NMS/Cordell Bank NMS, Moderated by Jason Britton of NewDay.

8:00 PM Event ends

# Ocean Film Screening - Sequoias of the Sea

Hosted by Ana Blanco & 5 others

Apr

24

Thursday, April 24

6:00 PM - 8:00 PM PDT

Register to See Address

San Francisco, California

Suggested Donation

$25.00

Pay what you want

Welcome! To join the event, please get your ticket below.

Get Ticket

You will be asked to verify token ownership with your wallet.

About Event

​Special Screening of the IOFF Official Selection and Award Winning film Sequoias of the Sea, followed by Q&A with the film directors.

​More than 95% of the kelp forests have disappeared along the Northern California Coast. SEQUOIAS OF THE SEA tells the story of the environmental, cultural and economic destruction impacting a coastal town that has lost its coastal kelp forest. It’s a deep dive into the lives of fishermen, tribes, scientists, and a community working to restore a habitat devastated by a warming climate.

​Be part of the movement to save our underwater forests. Connect with passionate conservationists, engage in meaningful discussions, and learn how we can work together to restore our coastal habitats.

​Reserve your spot today!

​ **Schedule:**

​6:00 PM Arrival, reception and networking

6:15 PM Welcome remarks

6:30 PM **_Sequoias of the Sea_** Documentary Film (54 min)

7:30 PM Panel Discussion with Film Directors Ana Blanco, Natasha Benjamin, and Maria Brown, Superintendent of Greater Farallones NMS/Cordell Bank NMS, Moderated by Jason Britton of NewDay.

8:00 PM Event ends

​“ _By registering for this event, you agree to share your registration information with the organizers of SF Climate Week.”_

About Event

​You are invited to an exclusive event hosted by [Brex.](http://brex.com/)

​From athlete to entrepreneur: a panel discussion in San Francisco.

- ​Panelists:

  - ​ [Baron Davis](https://www.linkedin.com/in/barondavis/) -Two-Time NBA All-Star, Founder and CEO, Business Inside the Game (BIG)

  - ​ [Anshul Shah](https://www.linkedin.com/in/shahanshul/) \- Head of Accounting & CFO Partnerships, VC Ambassador at Brex)

​ [Baron Davis](https://www.barondavisenterprises.com/lander) is a two-time NBA All-Star, serial entrepreneur, investor, and creator of thought-provoking content and digital platforms. During his years in the NBA, Davis was constantly listening, learning, networking, and connecting both on the court and off, which ignited a successful post-NBA business career. Through the process of being his own agent, he fast-forwarded in the role of being a business owner. He decided to use his platform and the knowledge he gained to support others by investing and funding entrepreneurs and start-ups that he believes in, including those created to impact society and encourage change. Davis has also become an outspoken advocate for financial literacy, ed-tech, and VC leaders from underrepresented communities.

About Event

​You are invited to an exclusive event hosted by [Brex.](http://brex.com/)

​From athlete to entrepreneur: a panel discussion in San Francisco.

- ​Panelists:

  - ​ [Baron Davis](https://www.linkedin.com/in/barondavis/) -Two-Time NBA All-Star, Founder and CEO, Business Inside the Game (BIG)

  - ​ [Anshul Shah](https://www.linkedin.com/in/shahanshul/) \- Head of Accounting & CFO Partnerships, VC Ambassador at Brex)

​ [Baron Davis](https://www.barondavisenterprises.com/lander) is a two-time NBA All-Star, serial entrepreneur, investor, and creator of thought-provoking content and digital platforms. During his years in the NBA, Davis was constantly listening, learning, networking, and connecting both on the court and off, which ignited a successful post-NBA business career. Through the process of being his own agent, he fast-forwarded in the role of being a business owner. He decided to use his platform and the knowledge he gained to support others by investing and funding entrepreneurs and start-ups that he believes in, including those created to impact society and encourage change. Davis has also become an outspoken advocate for financial literacy, ed-tech, and VC leaders from underrepresented communities.

​ **Please RSVP, space is limited.**

​ **A note to prospective guests:**

Admitted guests will be notified by way of event approval (with calendar invite). Invites are non-transferable. Additional correspondence will be sent leading up to the event.

​ **Event Details:**

​​📅 Date: April 8th, 2024

​​⏰ Agenda:

​5.45 - 6.30 - Networking

​6.30-7.30- Fireside chat

​​🔒 Venue: Revealed upon RSVP (San Francisco)

​ [Brex](http://brex.com/) is the modern spend platform for finance teams and founders looking to make every dollar count. Brex combines financial services and software to streamline workflows, unlock real-time visibility, and control spend before it happens — offering the world’s smartest corporate card, banking, expense management, and travel on one AI-powered platform. Through Brex’s products, financial expertise, and world-class service, customers eliminate 60% of manual tasks — saving over 11 million hours of employee effort. Recognized as an industry leader by Forbes, Fast Company, Deloitte, Fortune, and others, Brex serves 30,000+ of the world’s best companies.

​ **Events code of conduct**

- ​​​​​​You will be considerate, respectful, and follow the event venue’s rules and policies, and applicable laws.

- ​​​​​​You will not engage in harassment, discrimination, demeaning conduct, unwelcome sexual advances (physical or verbal), threatening or intimidating language or conduct, or inappropriate photography or recording.

- ​​​​​Concerns? Reach out to your event host, or use [integrity.brex.com](http://integrity.brex.com/), our anonymous reporting portal.  Brex takes your concerns seriously, and people who raise good-faith concerns will not be retaliated against.

# SF Writing Club

[SF Writing Club's Calendar](https://lu.ma/sfWritingClubCalendar?k=c)

Apr

13

Sunday, April 13

10:00 AM - 11:30 AM PDT

Register to See Address

San Francisco, California

Welcome! To join the event, please register below.

Register

You will be asked to verify token ownership with your wallet.

About Event

​Welcome to SF Writing Club!

​​We're a community of writers, technologists, and builders. We convene once a week on Sunday mornings in Hayes Valley to meet cool people & go heads down together to write whatever's on our minds and hearts.

​​We welcome writing in all forms from journaling and personal introspection to technology and science fiction to cultural takes and everything in between.

​​ **✍️ What to Expect**

- ​​ **10AM**: Arrive at the space _by_ 10AM

- ​​ **10:00-10:20AM**: Meet cool people!

  - ​​Make some tea & chat ☕
- ​​ **10:20-10:30AM:** Intros & intention setting

  - ​​We kick off each session with a brief round of intros and set intentions for how we'll spend our time together
- ​​ **10:30-11:30AM**: Deep writing

  - ​​We go heads down for an hour (🤫🎧)
- ​​ **11:30AM**: Reflections

  - ​​After 60 minutes, we reconvene to reflect on our writing process together

  - ​​For those in the zone, you're welcome to continue to write

​​ **📍 Finding the space**: Please register to see the exact location! Hope to see you there :)

Location

# "The Great Yawn of History" Film Screening + Reception (Proceeds support the artist’s future projects.)

Hosted by Mohsen Hejrati & Hanieh Khaleghian

Apr

12

Saturday, April 12

3:00 PM - 5:00 PM PDT

[The New Parkway Theater\\
\\
Oakland, California](https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=The%20New%20Parkway%20Theater&query_place_id=ChIJFxykYquAj4ARmQ9p6V3m2LQ)

Welcome! Please choose your desired ticket type:

Get Ticket

You will be asked to verify token ownership with your wallet.

About Event

​ **🎬 Date & Time:**

April 12, 3:00 PM – 10:00 PM

• **Film Screening:** The New Parkway Theater (3:00–5:00 PM)

• **VIP Reception:** Nearby private residence (5:30–10:00 PM)

* * *

​Join us for a special screening of **_[The Great Yawn of History](https://www.imdb.com/title/tt31016912/)_** by **[Aliyar Rasti](https://www.imdb.com/name/nm9932495/?ref_=tt_ov_dr_1)** which received the Special Jury Prize in the Encounters section of Berlinale 2024, featuring **Saber Abar** and **[Mohammad Aghebati](https://www.imdb.com/name/nm5396916/?ref_=tt_ov_st_2)**.

​ [Film Teaser: Youtube](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cY0RMJNst-8&ab_channel=Berlinale-BerlinInternationalFilmFestival)

​If you are interested in the independent cinema scene of Iran and its emerging artists, join the **VIP Reception** afterward to meet with **[Mohammad Aghebati](https://www.imdb.com/name/nm5396916/?ref_=tt_ov_st_2)** (actor and producer) and **[Mehrnoush Alia](https://www.imdb.com/name/nm3234299/)**(producer). We will have a Q&A with them and the director. They will share stories from the hidden world of independent filmmaking in Iran and showcase emerging film projects. We’ll screen a few trailers and short films and provide drinks and food (as always).

​This is a great chance to meet fellow filmmakers, actors, and movie lovers while supporting bold, independent Iranian cinema. The collected funds will go directly to support these independent artists' upcoming film projects.

* * *

​ **Film Synopsis:** **[The Great Yawn of History](https://www.imdb.com/title/tt31016912/)**

​Beitollah dreams of gold coins in a cave. Seeking a non-religious assistant, he recruits Shoja via fake bills. They search caves across Iran unsuccessfully. An innkeeper suspects their quest and secretly follows on his motorcycle.

​ **Director Biography:** **[Aliyar Rasti](https://www.imdb.com/name/nm9932495/?ref_=tt_ov_dr_1)**

​Born in Tehran, Iran in 1988, he began his career in photography, video and video installations before gradually moving towards his true passion of filmmaking. He has made more than ten music videos for independent Iranian bands which have screened at various festivals. His first short film, _In Between_, won the Best Debut Film award at the 2018 Tirana International Film Festival. It was followed by _America_, his second short. Rasti's debut feature film, The Great Yawn of History, received the Special Jury Prize in the Encounters section of Berlinale 2024, marking a significant milestone in his career.

​ [Film Teaser: Youtube](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cY0RMJNst-8&ab_channel=Berlinale-BerlinInternationalFilmFestival)

* * *

​ **Ticket Tiers**

​🎟️ 1\. **Film Only Ticket**

Admission to the screening of _The Great Yawn of History._

🎟️ 2\. **Film Ticket + VIP Reception**

Admission to the screening of _The Great Yawn of History._

Invitation to the VIP Reception from 5:30 pm to 10 pm. Drinks and food included.

​All funds **go directly to the artists** to support their upcoming films.

Location

The New Parkway Theater

474 24th St, Oakland, CA 94612, USA

Exclusive Event: 6624 Saroni Drive
